<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-314-348  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 314 348.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Modern Office Technology  April 1990 v35 n4 p42(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Micrographics.(part of a special section on records management)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microform as an alternative to paper storage of records is tentimes cheaper than optical disk systems.andP;  Business images arecaptured by a camera, recorded on film or microfiche, and stored.andO;In computer output microfilming (COM), information is sentdirectly to microfilm from the computer without first beingprinted on paper.andP;  COM images can be created with a cathode raytube (CRT) photographed by the COM camera; with a laser, writingdirectly on the film; with an electron beam; or with lightemitting diodes (LEDs) and a fiber optics bundle.andP;  Opticalcharacter recognition (OCR) and bar coding seem likely to be addedto micrographics records management in the near future.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Records ManagementMicrographicsMicroform EquipmentOffice Automation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>